{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a6daa3f4-a5e1-4920-9a9d-6e114820795e","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Collect a trace (30 seconds):**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p $(pgrep -f dotnet) --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**3. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**4. Analyze** — open in Visual Studio, PerfView, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app) (convert first with `dotnet-trace convert --format speedscope`).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet-trace` can't be installed (read-only filesystem), use a **sidecar** or `dotnet-monitor` instead.\n- For production, consider deploying [`dotnet-monitor`](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-monitor) as a sidecar — it exposes an HTTP API to collect traces on-demand without exec'ing in.\n- If you need OS-level detail (native frames, kernel), use **`perf`** instead, but `dotnet-trace` is simpler for managed code.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"981c4581-b019-4547-b2be-f02a444dd48d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge question, not a code task. I'll provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":426},"id":"e22f746d-936a-4189-acee-88af5b3da517","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:55:20.224Z","parentId":"aaaf6c6f-9295-4c10-bf41-d8df485b75fb"}
